This popular science article explains how reproducibility fits into conversations on balancing trust and skepticism in science in the era of misinformation and distrust by providing reproducibility in research as a way to inspire confidence in the scientific process. It suggests that reproducibility is at the foundations of credibility through transparency of research â€“ which allows scientists to redo research, evaluate and analyse information and decisions made. This is shown through the debunking of the notorious and controversial paper that linked MMR vaccines to autism. There is a also video on reproducibility linked in the article to increase in accessibility and for further explanation. Finally, the article discussing methods to introduce reproducibility to learners in secondary school.  
Link: https://theconversation.com/reproducibility-may-be-the-key-idea-students-need-to-balance-trust-in-evidence-with-healthy-skepticism-251771
